      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It was with gratification and a sense of honor that I read ''21 Asian-Americans Receive Medal of Honor'' (news article, May 14), especially when I discovered that most were from the 442nd Regimental Combat Team, a Japanese-American unit in the United States Army in which I served.</p>
        <p>This is belated recognition, but still it is recognition.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It was with gratification and a sense of honor that I read ''21 Asian-Americans Receive Medal of Honor'' (news article, May 14), especially when I discovered that most were from the 442nd Regimental Combat Team, a Japanese-American unit in the United States Army in which I served.</p>
        <p>This is belated recognition, but still it is recognition.</p>
        <p>And it is an acknowledgment that there was prejudice not only in the award of medals, but in the treatment of Japanese-Americans, who were placed in segregated internment camps during the war.</p>
        <p>YEIICHI KELLY KUWAYAMA  Washington, May 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
